ht|k|at|^B@2
Bypass the Diamonds and show the major'you might get only one chance to bid. This is the modern treatment (some call it "Walsh.") The theory is that with a "one-bid" hand you bypass Diamonds so you can show your 4-card major. If you know you will get to bid twice, you can bid your Diamonds first (even with 4-4 in Diamonds and the major). When using this style, after the partnership starts 1@C-1@D, the opener should rebid 1NT with any balanced hand (even with a 4-card major). He can do so safely with the knowledge that a 4-4 major-suit fit won't be missed.
|ht|e|
cs|6|at|^p{|ia|,1cp1s|at|}|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


ht|q|at|^B@2For example, opener has: @SK J 9 3 @HK 7 4 @D7 3 @CA J 5 3

He opens 1@C and hears partner respond 1@D. He should rebid 1NT. He knows there is no chance of missing a 4-4 spade fit. (If there is one, then partner has a big hand and will bid spades next). The 1@D responder can't hold hand in examples (B) or (C) above. Reminder: if you are not using the "Walsh" (bypass Diamods) style, then opener would surely rebid 1@S with this hand.|
